### Feature: 3rd Match Candidate (Best Small-Offset Match) → ZXL7

#### Problem
match_find returned up to 2 candidates: best-savings match and shortest viable match.
When the global best match was a large-offset EXACT2/EXACT, the DP never got to
consider a shorter but cheaper EXACT1/DELTA1 match (off<256, lm<256). The DP overhead
difference between EXACT1 (ovhd_exact1 ≈ 24 bits) and EXACT (ovhd_exact ≈ 48 bits) can
be decisive for short matches — EXACT1 of length 4 saves ~12 bits; EXACT of length 4
saves nothing (negative savings).

#### Solution
Added a 3rd match candidate to match_find: best small-offset match with off<256 and
lm<256, regardless of match type. Tracked as `best_e1` / `best_e1_savings` in the
WALK_CHAIN macro. Only included in output if distinct from out[0] and out[1] by
(offset, length) pair.

Changes:
- `zxl_match.h`: Match out[2] → out[3], updated comment
- `zxl_match.c`: Added best_e1/best_e1_savings tracking to WALK_CHAIN macro.
  match_find returns 0–3 candidates; 3rd is the best small-offset match if distinct.
- `zxl_codec.c`: Added match_arr3 array. Forward scan stores tmp[2].
  DP backward pass: choice=4 → match_arr3[u], uses ovhd_exact1/delta1 overhead.
  Forward trace: ch==4 uses match_arr3[i].
  REP pre-pass: extended loop to consider candidate c==2 (match_arr3).

#### Benchmark Results (ZXL7)

  ntdll.dll    : 0.4625  (was 0.4630, −0.05 pts)
  kernel32.dll : 0.4599  (was 0.4605, −0.06 pts)
  user32.dll   : 0.3777  (was 0.3781, −0.04 pts)

  Compress:   0.4–0.9 MB/s (unchanged)
  Decompress: 185–216 MB/s

Small but consistent gain across all files. The feature helps at positions where the
globally best match is large-offset but a cheap small-offset match opens better downstream
coverage. The gain is modest because most EXACT1 candidates were already covered when
they happened to be the globally best match.

  Round-trip test: PASS

