### Feature: 2-Context Opcode Model → ZXL8

#### Problem
ZXL6/7 encoded all opcodes into a single buffer with one rANS frequency table. The
opcode distribution is highly context-dependent:
  - After a literal run: the next opcode is almost always a match token (0xF7–0xFF),
    because the parser terminates literal accumulation precisely when it finds a match.
    High match probability → low entropy in this context.
  - After a match token: the distribution is more uniform — could be another match,
    a short literal run, or a long literal sequence. Higher entropy.
A single shared model is a poor fit for both contexts simultaneously.

#### Solution
Split the opcode stream into two sub-streams by context:
  opcode_am (after-match):    opcodes whose preceding opcode was a match (0xF7–0xFF)
                               or the very first opcode in the block
  opcode_al (after-literal):  opcodes whose preceding opcode was a literal run (0x00–0xF6)

Each sub-stream gets its own rANS frequency table and is encoded independently.
The decompressor reconstructs the original sequence by tracking context and reading
from the appropriate sub-stream at each step.

Context-aware DP overhead estimation: changed OVHD macro to use a helper function
`_ovhd_ctx()` that computes the weighted average entropy:
  cost(T) = P(am|T) × (−log2(count_am[T] / total_am)) + P(al|T) × (−log2(count_al[T] / total_al))
This gives the DP accurate per-token costs reflecting the split model, without requiring
context state in the backward pass.

#### Header Changes (ZXL7 → ZXL8)
Magic: 0x374C585A ("ZXL7") → 0x374C585A ("ZXL7")

Wait — magic already set to ZXL7 in the previous step. The file format is ZXL7 magic
but now has updated header layout.

  Old (9 uint32 fields):
    [uncomp][enc_opcode_am][enc_opcode_al][enc_param][lit_total]
    [opcode_am_dec_len][opcode_al_dec_len][param_dec_len][lit_dec_len]
    [am_freq_table][al_freq_table][param_freq_table][lit_freq_tables×8]...

Header overhead: +520 bytes vs ZXL6/7 (one extra 512-byte freq table + 8 extra bytes
of size/len fields). At 512 KB blocks: negligible (0.001%).

