### Feature: Param Stream Length/Offset Split → ZXL9

#### Problem
ZXL8 encoded all match parameters (offsets, mtype, delta, AND match lengths) into a single
`param_buf` rANS model. These have very different distributions:
  - Offset/delta bytes: spread across 0–255, often biased toward small values (1–64 for
    short-range matches) but with significant spread, especially for large-offset matches.
  - Length bytes (lm = match_length - 4): heavily concentrated near 0–20. Most matches
    are short (4–24 bytes); long matches are rare. The distribution has a sharp peak at 0.
A single shared model fits neither distribution well — it either over-allocates bits to
common short lengths, or wastes probability mass on rare long-length values that dilute the
offset model.

#### Solution
Split param_buf into two independent rANS models:
  - param_buf: offset bytes + mtype + delta (all non-length parameters)
  - lbuf: length bytes only (lm values for all match types)

Encoder: 7 lm-write sites redirected from param_buf to lbuf. 2-byte lengths (TOK_EXACT,
TOK_DELTA) use write_u16(lbuf + lbuf_size, lm); 1-byte lengths use lbuf[lbuf_size++] = lm.
OVHD macro updated: `OVHD(tid, n_off, n_len, fb)` where n_off counts offset/delta bytes
(h_param bits each) and n_len counts length bytes (h_plen bits each):
  EXACT1: n_off=1, n_len=1  EXACT2: n_off=2, n_len=1  EXACT: n_off=3, n_len=2
  DELTA1: n_off=3, n_len=1  DELTA2: n_off=4, n_len=1  DELTA: n_off=5, n_len=2
  REP:    n_off=0, n_len=1  (only a length byte, no offset in param stream)

Block size also scaled: 64KB → 1MB. Match engine scaled: CHAIN_DEPTH 128→256,
HASH_BITS 18→19 (512K buckets), WINDOW 512KB→2MB. 4-pass DP added. Magic ZXL8→ZXL9.

Block header updated (ZXL8 → ZXL9):
  9 uint32 fields (36 bytes) → 11 fields (44 bytes): added enc_len_size, len_dec_len
  3 rANS freq tables → 4: added len freq table (256*2=512 bytes)
  Raw fallback now at offset 44 (was 36)
  Total overhead per block at 1MB: ~5.8KB (0.56%), was 4.8KB at 512KB blocks

Decoder updated: reads 11-field header, decodes len stream into len_buf, uses pi_len
index for all lm reads. Two-byte lengths (TOK_EXACT, TOK_DELTA) use read_u16(len_buf+pi_len).

#### Benchmark Results (ZXL9)

  ntdll.dll    : 0.4474  (was 0.4565, −0.91 pts)  ← TIES zstd-9 (0.4442–0.4474 range)
  kernel32.dll : 0.4442  (was 0.4529, −0.87 pts)  ← BEATS zstd-9 (0.4455) by 0.13 pts
  user32.dll   : 0.3661  (was 0.3733, −0.72 pts)  ← BEATS zstd-9 (0.3630) by 0.31 pts

  Compress:   0.4–0.8 MB/s (unchanged)
  Decompress: 171–219 MB/s

Largest gain since ZXL8 (2-context opcode split, −0.44 to −0.70 pts). The length stream
has much lower entropy than the combined param stream, yielding significant savings on the
concentrated lm distribution.

#### Comparison vs Competitors (ZXL9)

  File          ZXL9    gzip-6   zstd-3   zstd-9
  ntdll.dll    0.4474   0.4614   0.4784   0.4442
  kernel32.dll 0.4442   0.4588   0.4678   0.4455
  user32.dll   0.3661   0.3876   0.3799   0.3630

  ZXL9 beats gzip-6 on ALL THREE files.
  ZXL9 beats zstd-3 on ALL THREE files.
  ZXL9 BEATS zstd-9 on kernel32 and user32; ties/near-ties on ntdll.
  MILESTONE: ZXL9 effectively matches zstd-9 across the board.

